I am strongly pro-choice, but I am also pro-principle and I have a big issue with national elections or referendum campaigns being influenced by actors outside the state (whether Irish or non-Irish). It is not a matter for non-nationals living (regardless of claimed descent or otherwise) to be interfering with. If the no side was disproportionately financed by foreign bodies/organisations and it was to lead to a relative strengthening of their campaign, I can assure you that the yes side would no doubt be critical, because I would! I thought comparing Irish women not being able to get abortions with a woman who claimed to be raped by two men was extremely insensitive to rape victims. It is extremely unfair that women can't get abortions in their own country. 3000 women a year leave the country to get abortions, so the prohibition is not working. As with anything, if prohibition doesn't work, then legalise and regulate it.
But, the woman claimed to be physically and sexually assaulted. That is completely different to having health care options removed from you. This seems like the yes campaign was trying to harness a lot of negativity around the rape case and trying to get more yes votes from it. Politicising the case was a tactless and silly thing to do. 

Also, claiming the "patriarchy" is enforcing the 8th amendment is a bit misleading. Lots of women voted for implementation of the 8th amendment in the early 80s. There is a significant divide between generations and what their attitudes are towards a woman's  right to choose. Lots of young women are going to vote no as well. This is not just a male issue

You would think after all the aligations of collusion in the American election that Americans would be hesitant to meddle in the democratic process in other nations. SaoirseHowDidYouFeel: I felt condescended to by this video. There is an air of arrogance and coercion in this video and the message it communicates. To disagree or to have concerns with the messages portrayed in the video could result in labeling a person as "conservative" or "oppressive" or without compassion but gives no regard to the complexities of the issue. Whereas those who agree with the video are vindicated and justified for their opinions. It is not a black and white issue (also represented in the imagery of the video). By using actors the message of the video relies on celebrity rather than reality to appeal to voters. The experiences of real people who have varying views on this issue, whether in agreement or in disagreement should be presented. I feel angry that celebrities are employed to sway opinions based on their popularity, when their opinion doesn't matter any more than the person living next door.
GraphicPostersHowDidYouFeel: I felt frustrated that an aspect of the conversation on abortion was being silenced as it was considered upsetting. If the concern was due to the location of the posters then it would suggest there is an absence of conversation occurring on what these images represent. Additionally, there seemed to be no concern or consideration for Yes posters outside institutions that historically adopt an anti-abortion stance. An open conversation addressing all facets and realities of abortion is not being presented to the public and I feel angry and frustrated by this silence.
RonanMullenHowDidYouFeel: I agreed with what they were saying; there was an imbalance to the committee's proceedings. I was angry that the result seemed predetermined, and frustrated there was not a balanced representation throughout the course of the committee's work.
CarolNolanHowDidYouFeel: I felt concerned that politicians I vote for may not have the freedom to express their opinion and voice their concerns,not only for their own conscience but also on behalf of those who they are representing. It also caused me to feel concern concerning the future of abortion in Ireland if only politicians will have a say in legislating for its use, and they can be silenced by their own party. There needs to be dissenting voices in every debate to address all concerns.

SaoirseHowDidYouFeel: Exasperated. It is ridiculous that people would look to celebrities for advice on an issue like this. Why should their opinions matter any more than any other member of the public who does not have a background in science, medicine or law. While they are entitled to their opinions, they are not experts on this issue and our information should come from reliable sources. It is a dangerous that more than ever celebrities are influencing political discourse and I hope that people base their vote on reliable research and sources, rather than because their favourite actor/musician told them how to vote.

It was ludicrous that the committee claimed to be unable to find pro-life doctors and rejected to read out letters from pro-life speakers who could not or chose not to attend. It is unsurprising that many pro-life spears chose to opt out given the one sided nature of the committee. I found their voting on the issue before hearing all the speakers to be particularly appalling and believe that it shows that the committee had already made their minds up before hearings began.
CarolNolanHowDidYouFeel: Annoyed, but not surprised. Mary-Lou had said that she would do it if anyone voted against repealing. It does not seem particularly democratic and I feel the silencing of dissenting opinions is indicative of a swing in Ireland in which liberal voices silence conservative opinions, rather than the other way around as it had been before. This silencing of pro-life opinions is particularly bad in UCC where some of my friends  and my brother have told me that they are afraid to let people know that they are pro-life for fear of how people will react. We need civilized discourse on this issue, but that seems unlikely to happen.
